@node Introduction "AquaBulls v2.0 Documentation"

Introduction
~~~~~~~~~~~~
AquaBulls is a replacement for the AmiExpress 'B' command (for viewing the
normal bulletins). It is written in highly optimized C code for great
performance, and it can be made resident which gives faster startups. Now,
take a look at all the @{"features" Link Features}...
@endnode

@node Features "AquaBulls v2.0 Documentation"

Features
~~~~~~~~
- You can have both global bulletins (for all conferences) and conference
  specific ones! If AquaBulls can't find a bulletin in the current
  conference, then it looks for it in the global directory 'Bulletins:'
  (or whatever path you configure). But you can also have conferences
  where the global bulletins can't be accessed at all.

- Just like the built-in 'B' command, a bulletin can be specified on the
  command line. Then only that bulletin will be shown, after which
  AquaBulls exits. If the user writes NS after the bulletin number (even
  on the bulletin prompt inside the door), and you're running AmiExpress
  3.19 or higher, the bulletin is shown non-stop.

- It is flexible: @{"Configuration" Link Configuration} can be made in an icon or in a text file,
  whatever you like best.

- Two kinds of online updating are supported!

   1. Updating of all/several bulletins: When the door is started, it
      checks for a particular script file 'BullBatch.Script' (both in the
      conference and globally), and if it exists, the user gets the
      question (if he has enough access) whether he wants the bulletins to
      be updated or not, i.e. if the script should be executed.

   2. Updating of specific bulletins: When a bulletin has been selected,
      the door checks if the update script for that bulletin exists and if
      it does, it is automatically executed. But the door can also be made
      to ask the user if he wants the script to be executed or not.

  Note that if you don't want to use online updating, you don't have to!!
  Just don't create any script files. But online updating can shorten your
  logoff script drastically because you can remove much of the bulletin
  updating stuff from it.

- The screen types (different text formats or languages) in AmiExpress
  3.0+ (configurable in BBS:ScreenTypes.info) are supported. The door
  first looks for the bulletin of the screen type selected by the user and
  if it doesn't  exist it then tries the bulletin ending with ".TXT".

- With AmiExpress 2.xx, bulletins ending with ".TXT.GR" are first looked
  for (but only if ANSI is on), and if it can't be found, the ".TXT"
  bulletin is shown.

- The screen is automatically cleared before each bulletin is shown.

- 'Who' doors show that the user is viewing bulletins when he's using
  AquaBulls. In fact, this was the thing that made me write this door. I
  was going to install a bulletin viewer on Nightfall and I tested several
  doors but all of them showed up in the who door as MODULE, not
  VIEWING BULLETINS! Very annoying... :)

- Whether a user has access to read bulletins or not is determined from
  the access icons (/X 3.0+, tooltype ACS.READ_BULLETINS) or the CONFIG(x)
  file (/X 2.xx). But the door doesn't read those files. It still knows.
  So it doesn't matter if you set the door access "too low".

- It allows you to write your own output (the BullHelp.txt)... Also, most
  strings in the door are totally configurable, for example the bulletin
  prompt. So you can choose colours yourself so that they match your
  BullHelp.txt and bulletins.
@endnode

@node Requirements "AquaBulls v2.0 Documentation"

Requirements
~~~~~~~~~~~~
- An Amiga with OS 2.0 or higher.

- AmiExpress, SigmaExpress or any compatible program.
@endnode

@node Installation "AquaBulls v2.0 Documentation"

Installation
~~~~~~~~~~~~
First, copy the 'AquaBulls' directory (the inner one) to 'Doors:'.


For AmiExpress 2.xx (and SigmaExpress?), add this to your 'BBS.CMD' file:

----Cut here------------------------------------
*B        XM001Doors:AquaBulls/AquaBulls
----Cut here------------------------------------


For AmiExpress 3.xx/4.xx, just copy 'B.info' to your 'BBSCmd' drawer.

The door is "pure" and is therefore perfectly safe to make resident. The
changes you have to make to 'B.info' in that case are: Change the value of
the "LOCATION" tooltype to "AquaBulls", and add the tooltype "RESIDENT".


The conference specific bulletins are stored in the directory
'<conf path>Bulletins/'. The global bulletins are stored in the path you
configure with the @{"GLOBAL_DIR" Link GLOBAL_DIR} tooltype.

If you don't want it to be possible to access the global bulletins from a
certain conference, then create '<conf path>Bulletins/NoGlobalBulls'. The
contents don't matter. An empty file will do fine.


A script for online updating of all/several bulletins (the first kind
described in the @{"Features" Link Features} section) is called 'BullBatch.Script' and is
located in '<conf path>Bulletins/' or in '<global path>'. If the
'NoGlobalBulls' file exists, then the script in '<global path>' won't be
executed, but otherwise BOTH scripts will be executed (if they both
exist).


A script that updates a _specific_ bulletin every time it is selected is
called 'BULL<no>.script' and is located in the same directory as the
bulletin which it is supposed to create.


Now it's time to @{"configure" Link Configuration} the door...
@endnode

@node Configuration "AquaBulls v2.0 Documentation"

Configuration
~~~~~~~~~~~~~
Some people like icons, some don't. The sysop configuration can be done
either in an icon ('Doors:AquaBulls/AquaBulls.info'), or in a textfile if
you prefer that ('Doors:AquaBulls/AquaBulls.config'). AquaBulls first
looks for the icon so if you want to use the textfile you have to delete
the icon! The textfile should simply contain the tooltypes that would be
in the icon otherwise.

You may well use ANSI codes in the string tooltypes. Note that the escape
character can be entered in a string gadget (in your tooltype editor if
you're editing AquaBulls.info) using <LeftAmiga-Esc>,
<LeftAmiga-Shift-Esc> or <LeftAmiga-Ctrl-Esc> etc.

These are the various tooltypes in AquaBulls.info/AquaBulls.config:

@{" ALLQUE_ACS " Link ALLQUE_ACS}     @{" ONEQUE_ACS " Link ONEQUE_ACS}     @{" PROMPT_STR " Link PROMPT_STR}     @{" GLOBAL_DIR " Link GLOBAL_DIR}
@{" ALLUPD_DEF " Link ALLUPD_DEF}     @{" ONEUPD_DEF " Link ONEUPD_DEF}     @{" NOBULL_STR " Link NOBULL_STR}
@{" ALLANS_DEF " Link ALLANS_DEF}     @{" ONEANS_DEF " Link ONEANS_DEF}     @{" ERRINP_STR " Link ERRINP_STR}
@{" ALLQUE_STR " Link ALLQUE_STR}     @{" ONEQUE_STR " Link ONEQUE_STR}     @{" NAVAIL_STR " Link NAVAIL_STR}
@{" ALLUPD_STR " Link ALLUPD_STR}     @{" ONEUPD_STR " Link ONEUPD_STR}
@endnode

@node GLOBAL_DIR "AquaBulls v2.0 Documentation"

Template: GLOBAL_DIR=<path>                                     Required.
Example : GLOBAL_DIR=Bulletins:

This tooltype specifies <global path> - the directory for the global
bulletins. It MUST end with '/' or ':'. Suitable location is for example
'Bulletins:' or 'BBS:Bulletins/'.
@endnode

@node ALLQUE_ACS "AquaBulls v2.0 Documentation"

Template: ALLQUE_ACS=<access level>                             Required.
Example : ALLQUE_ACS=1

This tooltype specifies the access level required to get the question "Do
you want to update the bulletins first?" at startup, or whatever string
you configure with @{"ALLQUE_STR" Link ALLQUE_STR}. (I will call it the "update-all" question
from now on.) If the user answers Yes on that question, 'BullBatch.Script'
will be executed.
@endnode

@node ALLUPD_DEF "AquaBulls v2.0 Documentation"

Template: ALLUPD_DEF=(YES|NO)                                   Required.
Example : ALLUPD_DEF=YES

This tooltype determines what happens when the user hasn't got enough
access to get the "update-all" question (see @{"ALLQUE_ACS" Link ALLQUE_ACS}). If the
'BullBatch.Script' SHOULD be executed then, set it to YES, else to NO.
@endnode

@node ALLANS_DEF "AquaBulls v2.0 Documentation"

Template: ALLANS_DEF=(YES|NO)                                   Required.
Example : ALLANS_DEF=YES

This tooltype determines what the default answer is to the "update-all"
question, i.e. what the answer is if the user presses <Enter>. You have to
make sure that the question string (@{"ALLQUE_STR" Link ALLQUE_STR}) shows the correct default
('Y/n' or 'y/N' for example).
@endnode

@node ALLQUE_STR "AquaBulls v2.0 Documentation"

Template: ALLQUE_STR=<string>                                   Required.
Example : ALLQUE_STR=Do you want to update the bulletins first (y/N)?

This tooltype specifies the question if the user wants the bulletins to be
updated before any bulletins are shown (by executing 'BullBatch.Script').
The default answer is determined by the tooltype @{"ALLANS_DEF" Link ALLANS_DEF}.
@endnode

@node ALLUPD_STR "AquaBulls v2.0 Documentation"

Template: ALLUPD_STR=<string>                                   Required.
Example : ALLUPD_STR=Updating bulletins...

This string will be shown when the 'BullBatch.Script' is executed.
@endnode

@node ONEQUE_ACS "AquaBulls v2.0 Documentation"

Template: ONEQUE_ACS=<access level>                             Required.
Example : ONEQUE_ACS=300

This tooltype specifies the access level required to get the question "Do
you want to update this bulletin?" when a bulletin is selected, or
whatever string you configure with @{"ONEQUE_STR" Link ONEQUE_STR}. (I will call it the
"update-one" question from now on.) If the user answers Yes on that
question, 'Bull<no>.Script' will be executed.
@endnode

@node ONEUPD_DEF "AquaBulls v2.0 Documentation"

Template: ONEUPD_DEF=(YES|NO)                                   Required.
Example : ONEUPD_DEF=YES

This tooltype determines what happens when the user hasn't got enough
access to get the "update-one" question (see @{"ONEQUE_ACS" Link ONEQUE_ACS}). If the
'BULL<no>.Script' SHOULD be executed then, set it to YES, otherwise to NO.
@endnode

@node ONEANS_DEF "AquaBulls v2.0 Documentation"

Template: ONEANS_DEF=(YES|NO)                                   Required.
Example : ONEANS_DEF=YES

This tooltype determines what the default answer is to the "update-one"
question, i.e. what the answer is if the user presses <Enter>. You have to
make sure that the question string (@{"ONEQUE_STR" Link ONEQUE_STR}) shows the correct default
('Y/n' or 'y/N' for example).
@endnode

@node ONEQUE_STR "AquaBulls v2.0 Documentation"

Template: ONEQUE_STR=<string possibly containing '%ld'>         Required.
Example : ONEQUE_STR=Do you want to update this bulletin first (Y/n)?

This tooltype specifies the question if the user wants the bulletin to be
updated before it is shown (by executing 'BULL<no>.Script'). The default
answer is determined by the tooltype @{"ONEANS_DEF" Link ONEANS_DEF}. The tooltype can contain
the sequence '%ld' somewhere (but not more than one). The bulletin number
will be inserted there. No other '%' codes are allowed. But if you want a
'%' to be shown, enter '%%' in the tooltype.
@endnode

@node ONEUPD_STR "AquaBulls v2.0 Documentation"

Template: ONEUPD_STR=<string possibly containing '%ld'>         Required.
Example : ONEUPD_STR=Updating bulletin %ld...

This tooltype specifies the string that will be shown when a single
bulletin is updated (when BULL<no>.Script is executed). It can contain the
sequence '%ld' somewhere (but not more than one). The bulletin number will
be inserted there. No other '%' codes are allowed. But if you want a '%'
to be shown, enter '%%' in the tooltype.
@endnode

@node PROMPT_STR "AquaBulls v2.0 Documentation"

Template: PROMPT_STR=<string>                                   Required.
Example : PROMPT_STR=Which bulletin (?)=List, (Enter)=None?

This string will be shown as the bulletin prompt inside the door.
@endnode

@node NOBULL_STR "AquaBulls v2.0 Documentation"

Template: NOBULL_STR=<string possibly containing '%ld'>         Required.
Example : NOBULL_STR=Sorry, there is no bulletin %ld!

This tooltype specifies the string that will be shown when the user types
a valid number >= 0 and no bulletin 'BULL<no>.<suffix>' with that number
exists. The tooltype can contain the sequence '%ld' somewhere (but not
more than one). The bulletin number will be inserted there. No other '%'
codes are allowed. But if you want a '%' to be shown, enter '%%' in the
tooltype.
@endnode

@node ERRINP_STR "AquaBulls v2.0 Documentation"

Template: ERRINP_STR=<string>                                   Required.
Example : ERRINP_STR=Invalid input! No such bulletin!

This string will be shown when the user gives invalid input on the
bulletin prompt.
@endnode

@node NAVAIL_STR "AquaBulls v2.0 Documentation"

Template: NAVAIL_STR=<string>                                   Required.
Example : NAVAIL_STR=No bulletins are available in this conference!

This string will be shown if no bulletins can be found. (Actually, if no
'BullHelp.<suffix>' can be found.)
@endnode


@node Algorithms "AquaBulls v2.0 Documentation"

Algorithms
~~~~~~~~~~
Here is an attempt to describe the way AquaBulls works. If you don't
understand a jot, use SnoopDos or some similar program to figure it out..

When the door is started, it works like this (presuming that a BullHelp
file could be found):

  If '<conf path>Bulletins/BullBatch.Script' exists,
     or
       '<conf path>Bulletins/NoGlobalBulls' doesn't exist and
       '<global path>BullBatch.Script' exists, then

    Ask the user if the bulletins should be updated (provided he has the
    access defined by @{"ALLQUE_ACS" Link ALLQUE_ACS}).
    If YES then
       If '<conf path>Bulletins/BullBatch.Script' exists then execute it.
       If '<conf path>Bulletins/NoGlobalBulls' doesn't exist, then
          Try to execute '<global path>BullBatch.Script'.

  Show the BullHelp (plus screen type suffix or '.TXT').
  Wait for the user to select a bulletin number.


The door works like this when the user has selected a bulletin to view:

  If '<conf path>Bulletins/BULL<no>.Script' exists, ask if the user wants
  it to be executed (provided he has the access defined by @{"ONEQUE_ACS" Link ONEQUE_ACS}).
  If YES then execute it.

  Try to show '<conf path>Bulletins/BULL<no>.<screen type suffix>' (/X 3).
  If it failed, try to show '<conf path>Bulletins/BULL<no>.TXT'.

  If that failed too, and if '<conf path>Bulletins/NoGlobalBulls' doesn't
  exist then continue with:

     If '<global path>BULL<no>.Script' exists, ask if the user wants it
     to be executed (provided he has the access defined by @{"ONEQUE_ACS" Link ONEQUE_ACS}).
     If YES then execute it.

     Try to show '<global path>BULL<no>.<screen type suffix>'.
     If it failed, try to show '<global path>BULL<no>.TXT'.


The BullHelp is searched for in a corresponding way (no script files for
that).
@endnode

@node History "AquaBulls v2.0 Documentation"

History
~~~~~~~
1.0 (04-24-94) First release version.


1.1 (01-11-95) For beta testers only.

               Made it residentable and halved the size of the door!

               It now shows the door version ([-AquaBulls vX.X-] instead
               of just [-AquaBulls-]).

               Made most strings configurable, using a bunch of tooltypes.

               If the user starts the door with 'B <bull> NS' (for example
               'B 18 NS'), the bulletin is displayed non-stop. You can
               also write '<bull> NS' on the prompt inside the door...
               /X 3.19 is required for this. In other versions the
               bulletin will be displayed normally, with pauses.

               Added tooltype GLOBAL_DIR=<dir for global bulletins>.

               If the user gave a bulletin number as argument to the door,
               it didn't ask if he wanted to update the bulletins first.
               Fixed that.


2.0 (01-21-95) Second release version.

               The S flag is no longer required on the script files.
               Instead, the command EXECUTE must be in your C: directory
               or be resident.

               Revised the tooltypes. Changed a lot. 'ACS.UPDATE' is no
               longer in use.

               Added support for a text file as configuration.
               ('Doors:AquaBulls/AquaBulls.config'.) 'AquaBulls.info' is
               searched for first.
@endnode

